# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: http-caching-strategies
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The HTTP **`Cache-Control`** header holds *directives* (instructions) in both requests and responses that control caching in browsers and shared caches (e.g., Proxies, CDNs).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note: Check the compatibility table for their support; user agents that don't recognize them should ignore them.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This section defines the terms used in this document, some of which are from the specification.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Implementation that holds requests and responses for reusing in subsequent requests.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It can be either a shared cache or a private cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Cache that exists between the origin server and clients (e.g., Proxy, CDN).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It stores a single response and reuses it with multiple users — so developers should avoid storing personalized contents to be cached in the shared cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It is also called *local cache* or *browser cache*.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It can store and reuse personalized content for a single user.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Store a response in caches when the response is cacheable.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] However, the cached response is not always reused as-is.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Reuse cached responses for subsequent requests.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Ask the origin server whether or not the stored response is still fresh.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Usually, the revalidation is done through a conditional request.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This usually means the response can be reused for subsequent requests, depending on request directives.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Indicates that the response is a stale response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This usually means the response can't be reused as-is.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Cache storage isn't required to remove stale responses immediately because revalidation could change the response from being stale to being fresh again.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The time since a response was generated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It is a criterion for whether a response is fresh or stale.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This section lists directives that affect caching — both response directives and request directives.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `max-age=N` response directive indicates that the response remains fresh until *N* seconds after the response is generated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Indicates that caches can store this response and reuse it for subsequent requests while it's fresh.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that `max-age` is not the elapsed time since the response was received; it is the elapsed time since the response was generated on the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] So if the other cache(s) — on the network route taken by the response — store the response for 100 seconds (indicated using the `Age` response header field), the browser cache would deduct 100 seconds from its freshness lifetime.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If the `max-age` value is negative (for example, `-1`) or isn't an integer (for example, `3599.99`), then the caching behavior is unspecified.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Caches are encouraged to treat the value as if it were `0` (this is noted in the Calculating Freshness Lifetime section of the HTTP specification).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `s-maxage` response directive indicates how long the response remains fresh in a shared cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `s-maxage` directive is ignored by private caches, and overrides the value specified by the `max-age` directive or the `Expires` header for shared caches, if they are present.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `no-cache` response directive indicates that the response can be stored in caches, but the response must be validated with the origin server before each reuse, even when the cache is disconnected from the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If you want caches to always check for content updates while reusing stored content, `no-cache` is the directive to use.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] It does this by requiring caches to revalidate each request with the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that `no-cache` does not mean "don't cache".
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `no-cache` allows caches to store a response but requires them to revalidate it before reuse.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If the sense of "don't cache" that you want is actually "don't store", then `no-store` is the directive to use.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `must-revalidate` response directive indicates that the response can be stored in caches and can be reused while fresh.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If the response becomes stale, it must be validated with the origin server before reuse.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Typically, `must-revalidate` is used with `max-age`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] HTTP allows caches to reuse stale responses when they are disconnected from the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `must-revalidate` is a way to prevent this from happening - either the stored response is revalidated with the origin server or a 504 (Gateway Timeout) response is generated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `proxy-revalidate` response directive is the equivalent of `must-revalidate`, but specifically for shared caches only.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `no-store` response directive indicates that any caches of any kind (private or shared) should not store this response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `private` response directive indicates that the response can be stored only in a private cache (e.g., local caches in browsers).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] You should add the `private` directive for user-personalized content, especially for responses received after login and for sessions managed via cookies.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If you forget to add `private` to a response with personalized content, then that response can be stored in a shared cache and end up being reused for multiple users, which can cause personal information to leak.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `public` response directive indicates that the response can be stored in a shared cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Responses for requests with `Authorization` header fields must not be stored in a shared cache; however, the `public` directive will cause such responses to be stored in a shared cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In general, when pages are under Basic Auth or Digest Auth, the browser sends requests with the `Authorization` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This means that the response is access-controlled for restricted users (who have accounts), and it's fundamentally not shared-cacheable, even if it has `max-age`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] You can use the `public` directive to unlock that restriction.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that `s-maxage` or `must-revalidate` also unlock that restriction.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If a request doesn't have an `Authorization` header, or you are already using `s-maxage` or `must-revalidate` in the response, then you don't need to use `public`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `must-understand` response directive indicates that a cache should store the response only if it understands the requirements for caching based on status code.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `must-understand` should be coupled with `no-store` for fallback behavior.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If a cache doesn't support `must-understand`, it will be ignored.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If `no-store` is also present, the response isn't stored.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If a cache supports `must-understand`, it stores the response with an understanding of cache requirements based on its status code.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Some intermediaries transform content for various reasons.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] For example, some convert images to reduce transfer size.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In some cases, this is undesirable for the content provider.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `no-transform` indicates that any intermediary (regardless of whether it implements a cache) shouldn't transform the response contents.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `immutable` response directive indicates that the response will not be updated while it's fresh.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] A modern best practice for static resources is to include version/hashes in their URLs, while never modifying the resources — but instead, when necessary, *updating* the resources with newer versions that have new version-numbers/hashes, so that their URLs are different.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] That's called the **cache-busting** pattern.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] When a user reloads the browser, the browser will send conditional requests for validating to the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] But it's not necessary to revalidate those kinds of static resources even when a user reloads the browser, because they're never modified.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `immutable` tells a cache that the response is immutable while it's fresh and avoids those kinds of unnecessary conditional requests to the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] When you use a cache-busting pattern for resources and apply them to a long `max-age`, you can also add `immutable` to avoid revalidation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `stale-while-revalidate` response directive indicates that the cache could reuse a stale response while it revalidates it to a cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In the example above, the response is fresh for 7 days (604800s).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] After 7 days it becomes stale, but the cache is allowed to reuse it for any requests that are made in the following day (86400s), provided that they revalidate the response in the background.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Revalidation will make the cache be fresh again, so it appears to clients that it was always fresh during that period — effectively hiding the latency penalty of revalidation from them.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If no request happened during that period, the cache became stale and the next request will revalidate normally.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `stale-if-error` response directive indicates that the cache can reuse a stale response when an upstream server generates an error, or when the error is generated locally.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Here, an error is considered any response with a status code of 500, 502, 503, or 504.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Afterwards, it becomes stale, but can be used for an extra 1 day (86400s) when an error is encountered.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] After the stale-if-error period passes, the client will receive any error generated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `no-cache` request directive asks caches to validate the response with the origin server before reuse.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `no-cache` allows clients to request the most up-to-date response even if the cache has a fresh response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Browsers usually add `no-cache` to requests when users are **force reloading** a page.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `no-store` request directive allows a client to request that caches refrain from storing the request and corresponding response — even if the origin server's response could be stored.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `max-age=N` request directive indicates that the client allows a stored response that is generated on the origin server within *N* seconds — where *N* may be any non-negative integer (including `0`).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In the case above, if the response with `Cache-Control: max-age=10800` was generated more than 3 hours ago (calculated from `max-age` and the `Age` header), the cache couldn't reuse that response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Many browsers use this directive for **reloading**, as explained below.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `max-age=0` is a workaround for `no-cache`, because many old (HTTP/1.0) cache implementations don't support `no-cache`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Recently browsers are still using `max-age=0` in "reloading" — for backward compatibility — and alternatively using `no-cache` to cause a "force reloading".
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Caches are encouraged to treat the value as if it were `0`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `max-stale=N` request directive indicates that the client allows a stored response that is stale within *N* seconds.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If no *N* value is specified, the client will accept a stale response of any age.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] For example, a request with the header above indicates that the browser will accept a stale response from the cache that has expired within the last hour.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Clients can use this header when the origin server is down or too slow and can accept cached responses from caches even if they are a bit old.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that the major browsers do not support requests with `max-stale`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `min-fresh=N` request directive indicates that the client allows a stored response that is fresh for at least *N* seconds.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In the case above, if the response with `Cache-Control: max-age=3600` was stored in caches 51 minutes ago, the cache couldn't reuse that response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Clients can use this header when the user requires the response to not only be fresh, but also requires that it won't be updated for a period of time.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that the major browsers do not support requests with `min-fresh`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Same meaning that `no-transform` has for a response, but for a request instead.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The client indicates that an already-cached response should be returned.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If a cache has a stored response, even a stale one, it will be returned.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If no cached response is available, a 504 Gateway Timeout response will be returned.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The `stale-if-error` request directive indicates that the browser is interested in receiving stale content on error from any intermediate server for a particular origin.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] This is not supported by any browser (see Browser compatibility).
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If you don't want a response stored in caches, use the `no-store` directive.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that `no-cache` means "it can be stored but don't reuse before validating" — so it's not for preventing a response from being stored.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In theory, if directives are conflicted, the most restrictive directive should be honored.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] So the example below is basically meaningless because `private`, `no-cache`, `max-age=0` and `must-revalidate` conflict with `no-store`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] When you build static assets with versioning/hashing mechanisms, adding a version/hash to the filename or query string is a good way to manage caching.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] The React library version will change when you update the library, and `hero.png` will also change when you edit the picture.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] So those are hard to store in a cache with `max-age`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] In such a case, you could address the caching needs by using a specific, numbered version of the library, and including the hash of the picture in its URL.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] You can add a long `max-age` value and `immutable` because the content will never change.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] When you update the library or edit the picture, new content should have a new URL, and caches aren't reused.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] That is called the "cache busting" pattern.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Use a `no-cache` to make sure that the HTML response itself is not cached.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `no-cache` could cause revalidation, and the client will correctly receive a new version of the HTML response and static assets.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note: If `index.html` is controlled under Basic Authentication or Digest Authentication, files under `/assets` are not stored in the shared cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If `/assets/` files are suitable for storing in a shared cache, you also need one of `public`, `s-maxage` or `must-revalidate`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] For content that's generated dynamically, or that's static but updated often, you want a user to always receive the most up-to-date version.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] If you don't add a `Cache-Control` header because the response is not intended to be cached, that could cause an unexpected result.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Cache storage is allowed to cache it heuristically — so if you have any requirements on caching, you should always indicate them explicitly, in the `Cache-Control` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Adding `no-cache` to the response causes revalidation to the server, so you can serve a fresh response every time — or if the client already has a new one, just respond `304 Not Modified`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Most HTTP/1.0 caches don't support `no-cache` directives, so historically `max-age=0` was used as a workaround.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] But only `max-age=0` could cause a stale response to be reused when caches disconnected from the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] That's why the example below is equivalent to `no-cache`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] But for now, you can simply use `no-cache` instead.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] There are no cache directives for clearing already-stored responses from caches on *intermediate* servers.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Imagine that clients/caches store a fresh response for a path, with no request flight to the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] There is nothing a server could do to that path.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] `Clear-Site-Data: cache` can be used to clear every stored response for a site in the browser cache, so use this with care.
[src:http-caching-strategies/cache-control] Note that this will not affect shared or intermediate caches.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The HTTP cache stores a response associated with a request and reuses the stored response for subsequent requests.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] There are several advantages to reusability.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] First, since there is no need to deliver the request to the origin server, then the closer the client and cache are, the faster the response will be.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The most typical example is when the browser itself stores a cache for browser requests.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Also, when a response is reusable, the origin server does not need to process the request — so it does not need to parse and route the request, restore the session based on the cookie, query the DB for results, or render the template engine.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Proper operation of the cache is critical to the health of the system.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In the HTTP Caching spec, there are two main types of caches: **private caches** and **shared caches**.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] A private cache is a cache tied to a specific client — typically a browser cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Since the stored response is not shared with other clients, a private cache can store a personalized response for that user.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] On the other hand, if personalized contents are stored in a cache other than a private cache, then other users may be able to retrieve those contents — which may cause unintentional information leakage.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If a response contains personalized content and you want to store the response only in the private cache, you must specify a `private` directive.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Personalized contents are usually controlled by cookies, but the presence of a cookie does not always indicate that it is private, and thus a cookie alone does not make the response private.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The shared cache is located between the client and the server and can store responses that can be shared among users.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] And shared caches can be further sub-classified into **proxy caches** and **managed caches**.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In addition to the function of access control, some proxies implement caching to reduce traffic out of the network.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] This is usually not managed by the service developer, so it must be controlled by appropriate HTTP headers and so on.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, in the past, outdated proxy-cache implementations — such as implementations that do not properly understand the HTTP Caching standard — have often caused problems for developers.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, in recent years, as HTTPS has become more common and client/server communication has become encrypted, proxy caches in the path can only tunnel a response and can't behave as a cache, in many cases.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] So in that scenario, there is no need to worry about outdated proxy cache implementations that cannot even see the response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, since CT (certificate transparency) has become widespread in recent years, and some browsers only allow certificates issued with an SCT (signed certificate timestamp), this method requires the application of an enterprise policy.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In such a controlled environment, there is no need to worry about the proxy cache being "out of date and not updated".
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Managed caches are explicitly deployed by service developers to offload the origin server and to deliver content efficiently.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Examples include reverse proxies, CDNs, and service workers in combination with the Cache API.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The characteristics of managed caches vary depending on the product deployed.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In most cases, you can control the cache's behavior through the `Cache-Control` header and your own configuration files or dashboards.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For example, the HTTP Caching specification essentially does not define a way to explicitly delete a cache — but with a managed cache, the stored response can be deleted at any time through dashboard operations, API calls, restarts, and so on.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] That allows for a more proactive caching strategy.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] It is also possible to ignore the standard HTTP Caching spec protocols in favor of explicit manipulation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For example, the following can be specified to opt-out of a private cache or proxy cache, while using your own strategy to cache only in a managed cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For example, Varnish Cache uses VCL (Varnish Configuration Language, a type of DSL) logic to handle cache storage, while service workers in combination with the Cache API allow you to create that logic in JavaScript.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] That means if a managed cache intentionally ignores a `no-store` directive, there is no need to perceive it as being "non-compliant" with the standard.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] What you should do is, avoid using kitchen-sink headers, but carefully read the documentation of whatever managed-cache mechanism you're using, and ensure you're controlling the cache properly in the ways provided by the mechanism you've chosen to use.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Note that some CDNs provide their own headers that are effective only for that CDN (for example, `Surrogate-Control`).
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Currently, work is underway to define a `CDN-Cache-Control` header to standardize those.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] HTTP is designed to cache as much as possible, so even if no `Cache-Control` is given, responses will get stored and reused if certain conditions are met.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For example, take the following response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] This response was last updated 1 year ago.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] It is heuristically known that content which has not been updated for a full year will not be updated for some time after that.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Therefore, the client stores this response (despite the lack of `max-age`) and reuses it for a while.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] How long to reuse is up to the implementation, but the specification recommends about 10% (in this case 0.1 year) of the time after storing.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Heuristic caching is a workaround that came before `Cache-Control` support became widely adopted, and basically all responses should explicitly specify a `Cache-Control` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Stored HTTP responses have two states: **fresh** and **stale**.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The *fresh* state usually indicates that the response is still valid and can be reused, while the *stale* state means that the cached response has already expired.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The criterion for determining when a response is fresh and when it is stale is **age**.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In HTTP, age is the time elapsed since the response was generated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] This is similar to the TTL in other caching mechanisms.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The cache that stored the example response calculates the time elapsed since the response was generated and uses the result as the response's *age*.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] As long as the stored response remains fresh, it will be used to fulfill client requests.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] When a response is stored in a shared cache, it is possible to tell the client the age of the response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Continuing with the example, if the shared cache stored the response for one day, the shared cache would send the following response to subsequent client requests.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The client which receives that response will find it to be fresh for the remaining 518400 seconds, the difference between the response's `max-age` and `Age`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In HTTP/1.0, freshness used to be specified by the `Expires` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `Expires` header specifies the lifetime of the cache using an explicit time rather than by specifying an elapsed time.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, the time format is difficult to parse, many implementation bugs were found, and it is possible to induce problems by intentionally shifting the system clock; therefore, `max-age` — for specifying an elapsed time — was adopted for `Cache-Control` in HTTP/1.1.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If both `Expires` and `Cache-Control: max-age` are available, `max-age` is defined to be preferred.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] So it is not necessary to provide `Expires` now that HTTP/1.1 is widely used.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] But the contents of responses are not always the same, even if they have the same URL.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Especially when content negotiation is performed, the response from the server can depend on the values of the `Accept`, `Accept-Language`, and `Accept-Encoding` request headers.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For example, for English content returned with an `Accept-Language: en` header and cached, it is undesirable to then reuse that cached response for requests that have an `Accept-Language: ja` request header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In this case, you can cause the responses to be cached separately — based on language — by adding `Accept-Language` to the value of the `Vary` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] That causes the cache to be keyed based on a composite of the response URL and the `Accept-Language` request header — rather than being based just on the response URL.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Also, if you are providing content optimization (for example, for responsive design) based on the user agent, you may be tempted to include `User-Agent` in the value of the `Vary` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, the `User-Agent` request header generally has a very large number of variations, which drastically reduces the chance that the cache will be reused.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] So if possible, instead consider a way to vary behavior based on feature detection rather than based on the `User-Agent` request header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For applications that employ cookies to prevent others from reusing cached personalized content, you should specify `Cache-Control: private` instead of specifying a cookie for `Vary`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Stale responses are not immediately discarded.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] HTTP has a mechanism to transform a stale response into a fresh one by asking the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] This is called **validation**, or sometimes, **revalidation**.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Validation is done by using a **conditional request** that includes an `If-Modified-Since` or `If-None-Match` request header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The following response was generated at 22:22:22 and has a `max-age` of 1 hour, so you know that it is fresh until 23:22:22.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] At 23:22:22, the response becomes stale and the cache cannot be reused.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] So the request below shows a client sending a request with an `If-Modified-Since` request header, to ask the server if there have been any changes made since the specified time.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The server will respond with `304 Not Modified` if the content has not changed since the specified time.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Since this response only indicates "no change", there is no response body — there's just a status code — so the transfer size is extremely small.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Upon receiving that response, the client reverts the stored stale response back to being fresh and can reuse it during the remaining 1 hour.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The server can obtain the modification time from the operating-system file system, which is relatively easy to do for the case of serving static files.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, there are some problems; for example, the time format is complex and difficult to parse, and distributed servers have difficulty synchronizing file-update times.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] To solve such problems, the `ETag` response header was standardized as an alternative.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The value of the `ETag` response header is an arbitrary value generated by the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] There are no restrictions on how the server must generate the value, so servers are free to set the value based on whatever means they choose — such as a hash of the body contents or a version number.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The server will return `304 Not Modified` if the value of the `ETag` header it determines for the requested resource is the same as the `If-None-Match` value in the request.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] But if the server determines the requested resource should now have a different `ETag` value, the server will instead respond with a `200 OK` and the latest version of the resource.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If you do not want a response to be reused, but instead want to always fetch the latest content from the server, you can use the `no-cache` directive to force validation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] By adding `Cache-Control: no-cache` to the response along with `Last-Modified` and `ETag` — as shown below — the client will receive a `200 OK` response if the requested resource has been updated, or will otherwise receive a `304 Not Modified` response if the requested resource has not been updated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] It is often stated that the combination of `max-age=0` and `must-revalidate` has the same meaning as `no-cache`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] `max-age=0` means that the response is immediately stale, and `must-revalidate` means that it must not be reused without revalidation once it is stale — so, in combination, the semantics seem to be the same as `no-cache`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, that usage of `max-age=0` is a remnant of the fact that many implementations prior to HTTP/1.1 were unable to handle the `no-cache` directive — and so to deal with that limitation, `max-age=0` was used as a workaround.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] But now that HTTP/1.1-conformant servers are widely deployed, there's no reason to ever use that `max-age=0` and `must-revalidate` combination — you should instead just use `no-cache`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `no-cache` directive does not prevent the storing of responses but instead prevents the reuse of responses without revalidation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If you don't want a response stored in any cache, use `no-store`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Under that set of circumstances, `no-store` is not always the most-appropriate directive.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The following sections look at the circumstances in more detail.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] It would be problematic if a response with personalized content is unexpectedly visible to other users of a cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In such a case, using the `private` directive will cause the personalized response to only be stored with the specific client and not be leaked to any other user of the cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In such a case, even if `no-store` is given, `private` must also be given.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `no-store` directive prevents a response from being stored, but does not delete any already-stored response for the same URL.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In other words, if there is an old response already stored for a particular URL, returning `no-store` will not prevent the old response from being reused.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, a `no-cache` directive will force the client to send a validation request before reusing any stored response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If the server does not support conditional requests, you can force the client to access the server every time and always get the latest response with `200 OK`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] As a workaround for outdated implementations that ignore `no-store`, you may see kitchen-sink headers such as the following being used.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] It is recommended to use `no-cache` as an alternative for dealing with such outdated implementations, and it is not a problem if `no-cache` is given from the beginning, since the server will always receive the request.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] You may think adding `no-store` would be the right way to opt-out of caching.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, it's not recommended to grant `no-store` liberally, because you lose many advantages that HTTP and browsers have, including the browser's back/forward cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Therefore, to get the advantages of the full feature set of the web platform, prefer the use of `no-cache` in combination with `private`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Validation can be performed for requests as well as responses.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The **reload** and **force reload** actions are common examples of validation performed from the browser side.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For recovering from window corruption or updating to the latest version of the resource, browsers provide a reload function for users.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `max-age=0` directive in the request specifies "reuse of responses with an age of 0 or less" — so, in effect, intermediately stored responses are not reused.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] As a result, a request is validated by `If-None-Match` and `If-Modified-Since`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Browsers use `max-age=0` during reloads for backward-compatibility reasons — because many outdated implementations prior to HTTP/1.1 did not understand `no-cache`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] But `no-cache` is fine now in this use case, and **force reload** is an additional way to bypass cached responses.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Since that's not a conditional request with `no-cache`, you can be sure you'll get a `200 OK` from the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Content that never changes should be given a long `max-age` by using cache busting — that is, by including a version number, hash value, etc., in the request URL.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, when the user reloads, a revalidation request is sent even though the server knows that the content is immutable.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] To prevent that, the `immutable` directive can be used to explicitly indicate that revalidation is not required because the content never changes.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] That prevents unnecessary revalidation during reloads.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Note that, instead of implementing that directive, Chrome has changed its implementation so that revalidation is not performed during reloads for subresources.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] There is no way to delete responses on an intermediate server that have been stored with a long `max-age`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Imagine that the following response from `https://example.com/` was stored.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] You may want to overwrite that response once it expired on the server, but there is nothing the server can do once the response is stored — since no more requests reach the server due to caching.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] One of the methods mentioned in the specification is to send a request for the same URL with an unsafe method such as `POST`, but for many clients that is difficult to do.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `Clear-Site-Data: cache` header and directive value can be used to clear browser caches — but has no effect on intermediate caches.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Otherwise responses will remain in the browser cache until `max-age` expires, unless the user manually performs a reload, force-reload, or clear-history action.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Caching reduces access to the server, which means that the server loses control of that URL.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If the server does not want to lose control of a URL — for example, in the case that a resource is frequently updated — you should add `no-cache` so that the server will always receive requests and send the intended responses.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The shared cache is primarily located before the origin server and is intended to reduce traffic to the origin server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Thus, if multiple identical requests arrive at a shared cache at the same time, the intermediate cache will forward a single request on behalf of itself to the origin, which can then reuse the result for all clients.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Request collapse occurs when requests are arriving at the same time, so even if `max-age=0` or `no-cache` is given in the response, it will be reused.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] (Request collapse shown as multiple clients sending GET requests and a cache consolidating them into one GET to the origin.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] There are many directives in the `Cache-Control` spec, and it may be difficult to understand all of them.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] But most websites can be covered by a combination of a handful of patterns.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] This section describes the common patterns in designing caches.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] As mentioned above, the default behavior for caching (that is, for a response without `Cache-Control`) is not simply "don't cache" but implicit caching according to so-called "heuristic caching".
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] To avoid that heuristic caching, it's preferable to explicitly give all responses a default `Cache-Control` header.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The resources that work best with caching are static immutable files whose contents never change.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] And for resources that *do* change, it is a common best practice to change the URL each time the content changes, so that the URL unit can be cached for a longer period.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In modern web development, JavaScript and CSS resources are frequently updated as development progresses.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Also, if the versions of JavaScript and CSS resources that a client uses are out of sync, the display will break.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] So the HTML above makes it difficult to cache `bundle.js` and `build.css` with `max-age`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Therefore, you can serve the JavaScript and CSS with URLs that include a changing part based on a version number or hash value.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Some of the ways to do that are shown below.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Since the cache distinguishes resources from one another based on their URLs, the cache will not be reused again if the URL changes when a resource is updated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] With that design, both JavaScript and CSS resources can be cached for a long time.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The QPACK specification provides an answer to that question.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] QPACK is a standard for compressing HTTP header fields, with tables of commonly-used field values defined.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Some commonly-used cache-header values are shown below.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If you select one of those numbered options, you can compress values in 1 byte when transferred via HTTP3.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Numbers `37`, `38`, and `41` are for periods of one week, one month, and one year.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Because the cache removes old entries when new entries are saved, the probability that a stored response still exists after one week is not that high — even if `max-age` is set to 1 week.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Therefore, in practice, it does not make much difference which one you choose.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Note that number `41` has the longest `max-age` (1 year), but with `public`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `public` value has the effect of making the response storable even if the `Authorization` header is present.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] So if the response is personalized with basic authentication, the presence of `public` may cause problems.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If you are concerned about that, you can choose the second-longest value, `38` (1 month).
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Don't forget to set the `Last-Modified` and `ETag` headers, so that you don't have to re-transmit a resource when reloading.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] It's easy to generate those headers for pre-built static files.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The `ETag` value here may be a hash of the file.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] In addition, `immutable` can be added to prevent validation on reload.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Unlike subresources, main resources cannot be cache busted because their URLs can't be decorated in the same way that subresource URLs can be.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] If the following HTML itself is stored, the latest version cannot be displayed even if the content is updated on the server side.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For that case, `no-cache` would be appropriate — rather than `no-store` — since we don't want to store HTML, but instead just want it to always be up-to-date.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] The same can be used for `favicon.ico`, `manifest.json`, `.well-known`, and API endpoints whose URLs cannot be changed using cache busting.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Most web content can be covered by a combination of the two patterns described above.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] With the method described in previous sections, subresources can be cached for a long time by using cache busting, but main resources (which are usually HTML documents) can't be.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] Caching main resources is difficult because, using just standard directives from the HTTP Caching specification, there's no way to actively delete cache contents when content is updated on the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] However, it is possible by deploying a managed cache such as a CDN or service worker.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For example, a CDN that allows cache purging via an API or dashboard operation would allow for a more aggressive caching strategy by storing the main resource and explicitly purging the relevant cache only when an update occurs on the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] A service worker could do the same if it could delete the contents in the Cache API when an update occurs on the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/guides-caching] For more information, see the documentation for your CDN, and consult the service worker documentation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-age] The HTTP **`Age`** response header indicates the time in seconds for which an object was in a proxy cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-age] The header value is usually close to zero.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-age] If the value is `0`, the object was probably fetched from the origin server; otherwise, the value is usually calculated as a difference between the proxy's current date and the `Date` general header included in the HTTP response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-age] A non-negative integer that represents the time in seconds for which the object was in a proxy cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] The HTTP **`ETag`** (entity tag) response header is an identifier for a specific version of a resource.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] It lets caches be more efficient and save bandwidth, as a web server does not need to resend a full response if the content has not changed.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Additionally, ETags help to prevent simultaneous updates of a resource from overwriting each other ("mid-air collisions").
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] If the resource at a given URL changes, a new `ETag` value *must* be generated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] A comparison of them can determine whether two representations of a resource are the same.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] `W/` (case-sensitive) indicates that a weak validator is used.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Weak ETags are easy to generate, but are far less useful for comparisons.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Strong validators are ideal for comparisons but can be very difficult to generate efficiently.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Weak `ETag` values of two representations of the same resources might be semantically equivalent, but not byte-for-byte identical.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] This means weak ETags prevent caching when byte range requests are used, but strong ETags mean range requests can still be cached.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Entity tag that uniquely represents the requested resource.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] It is a string of ASCII characters placed between double quotes, like `"675af34563dc-tr34"`.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] The method by which `ETag` values are generated is not specified.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Typically, the ETag value is a hash of the content, a hash of the last modification timestamp, or just a revision number.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] For example, a wiki engine can use a hexadecimal hash of the documentation article content.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] With the help of the `ETag` and the `If-Match` headers, you can detect mid-air edit collisions (conflicts).
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] When saving changes to a wiki page (posting data), the `POST` request will contain the `If-Match` header containing the `ETag` values to check freshness against.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] If the hashes don't match, it means that the document has been edited in-between and a `412 Precondition Failed` error is thrown.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-etag] Another typical use of the `ETag` header is to cache resources that are unchanged.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] The HTTP **`Vary`** response header describes the parts of the request message (aside from the method and URL) that influenced the content of the response it occurs in.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] Including a `Vary` header ensures that responses are separately cached based on the headers listed in the `Vary` field.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] Most often, this is used to create a cache key when content negotiation is in use.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] The same `Vary` header value should be used on all responses for a given URL, including `304` `Not Modified` responses and the "default" response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] Factors other than request headers influenced the generation of this response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] Implies that the response is uncacheable.
[src:http-caching-strategies/headers-vary] A request header name that could have influenced the generation of this response.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] A **web cache** (or **HTTP cache**) is a system for optimizing the World Wide Web.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] It is implemented both client-side and server-side.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] The caching of multimedia and other files can result in less overall delay when browsing the Web.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] A forward cache is a cache outside the web server's network, e.g. in the client's web browser, in an Internet service provider, or within a corporate network.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] A network-aware forward cache only caches heavily accessed items.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] A proxy server sitting between the client and web server can evaluate HTTP headers and choose whether to store web content.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] A reverse cache sits in front of one or more web servers, accelerating requests from the Internet and reducing peak server load.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] This is usually a content delivery network (CDN) that retains copies of web content at various points throughout a network.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] The Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) defines three basic mechanisms for controlling caches: freshness, validation, and invalidation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] This is specified in the header of HTTP response messages from the server.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] Freshness allows a response to be used without re-checking it on the origin server, and can be controlled by both the server and the client.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] For example, the Expires response header gives a date when the document becomes stale, and the Cache-Control: max-age directive tells the cache how many seconds the response is fresh for.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] Validation can be used to check whether a cached response is still good after it becomes stale.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] For example, if the response has a Last-Modified header, a cache can make a *conditional request* using the If-Modified-Since header to see if it has changed.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] The ETag (entity tag) mechanism also allows for both strong and weak validation.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] Invalidation is usually a side effect of another request that passes through the cache.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] For example, if a URL associated with a cached response subsequently gets a POST, PUT or DELETE request, the cached response will be invalidated.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] Many CDNs and manufacturers of network equipment have replaced this standard HTTP cache control with dynamic caching.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] In 1998, the Digital Millennium Copyright Act added rules to the United States Code (17 U.S.C. §: 512) that exempts system operators from copyright liability for the purposes of caching.
[src:http-caching-strategies/web-cache] This is a list of server-side web caching software.
